of the fifth district.

3
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:45,555
I'm sure some of you know we're
gathered here this afternoon...

4
00:01:45,557 --> 00:01:48,591
To dedicate the beginning
of a year long project:

5
00:01:48,593 --> 00:01:53,362
To make a movie right here in
Phoenix and the outlying areas,

6
00:01:53,364 --> 00:01:55,965
and much of it in our own fifth district.

7
00:02:00,872 --> 00:02:04,073
The fifth district is the home of our
good friends, the yeager family:

8
00:02:04,075 --> 00:02:07,009
Warren, Jeanette,
cute little Lisa and Eric.

9
00:02:07,011 --> 00:02:10,646
And they're going to be
the stars of this unusual movie.

10
00:02:10,648 --> 00:02:13,182
<i>Wait a minute.</i>

11
00:02:13,184 --> 00:02:16,619
<i>All of us in this room are</i> going to have
an important part <i>in the picture too.</i>

12
00:02:17,855 --> 00:02:20,790
My wife tells me
I'm not handsome enough...

13
00:02:20,792 --> 00:02:22,792
To be in the movies.

14
00:02:22,794 --> 00:02:25,995
But our guest of honor
here today says that's baloney.

15
00:02:25,997 --> 00:02:28,264
<i>He's the gentleman</i>
behind the whole thing.

16
00:02:28,266 --> 00:02:30,266
<i>Quite a gentleman</i> he is.

17
00:02:30,268 --> 00:02:32,802
Why, he's made me laugh on...

18
00:02:36,808 --> 00:02:39,308
"The tonight show," the late ed Sullivan.

19
00:02:39,310 --> 00:02:43,346
<i>And I know you've seen</i> his short films
on nbc's <i>"good night Saturday."</i>

20
00:02:43,348 --> 00:02:46,882
A lot of you have seen him on
your favorite shows, I'm sure.

21
00:02:46,884 --> 00:02:50,686
And if you like the food we had
today, you have him to thank.

22
00:02:50,688 --> 00:02:53,623
So would you please welcome
with a big Phoenix applause,

23
00:02:53,625 --> 00:02:56,092
all the way from Hollywood, California,

24
00:02:56,094 --> 00:02:57,960
Mr. Albert Brooks!

25
00:03:07,305 --> 00:03:09,138
Thank you, councilman Harris.

26
00:03:09,140 --> 00:03:13,643
Please tell the mayor
I wish him a speedy recovery.

27
00:03:13,645 --> 00:03:17,346
I couldn't help noticing some
expressions of shock or disbelief,

28
00:03:17,348 --> 00:03:19,148
or whatever it was you were doing,

29
00:03:19,150 --> 00:03:21,217
when the councilman mentioned
that the yeagers...

30
00:03:21,219 --> 00:03:24,820
Were going to be the stars
of a major motion picture.

31
00:03:24,822 --> 00:03:28,457
Many of you know Warren yeager
is a fine veterinarian...

32
00:03:28,459 --> 00:03:30,860
And not a professional actor.

33
00:03:30,862 --> 00:03:33,162
But that's exactly the point.

34
00:03:33,164 --> 00:03:37,600
We're gathered here this afternoon
to film Warren and his family,

35
00:03:37,602 --> 00:03:40,670
and you folks and ourselves as well,

36
00:03:40,672 --> 00:03:43,773
because we're making a movie
about reality.

37
00:03:49,547 --> 00:03:53,215
I'm sure you've all had the experience of
coming out of a motion picture theater...

38
00:03:53,217 --> 00:03:57,953
And saying to yourselves, "I've had
more interesting things happen to me..."

39
00:03:57,955 --> 00:04:00,790
"Than happened to those
characters in that picture.

40
00:04:00,792 --> 00:04:03,592
My life is
much more interesting."

41
00:04:03,594 --> 00:04:06,595
You know something?
You're right.

42
00:04:06,597 --> 00:04:09,165
The most hilarious comedy,

43
00:04:09,167 --> 00:04:11,333
the most gripping drama,

44
00:04:11,335 --> 00:04:14,036
the most suspenseful disasters,

45
00:04:14,038 --> 00:04:15,838
they don't happen on the movie screen.

46
00:04:16,974 --> 00:04:19,308
They happen in my backyard and yours.

47
00:04:24,749 --> 00:04:28,250
Thank you.
Thank you so much.

48
00:04:28,252 --> 00:04:31,253
So, please, just remember
two simple words...

49
00:04:31,255 --> 00:04:32,955
And everything will be perfect.

50
00:04:32,957 --> 00:04:34,857
Be yourselves.

51
00:04:34,859 --> 00:04:38,427
If you see our cameraman following Warren
or Jeanette, or one of the children...

52
00:04:38,429 --> 00:04:42,932
Into your homes, offices, cleaning
establishments or gas stations,

53
00:04:42,934 --> 00:04:45,234
don't try to do anything special.

54
00:04:45,236 --> 00:04:49,872
It's tempting to show off for the camera.
I know. I make my living that way.

55
00:04:49,874 --> 00:04:53,242
But in this case, we don't want a show.

56
00:04:53,244 --> 00:04:55,044
Let me correct myself.

57
00:04:55,046 --> 00:04:59,215
We want the greatest
show of all: Life!

58
00:04:59,217 --> 00:05:00,883
<i>Hey, you're great!</i>
You're great!

59
00:05:02,620 --> 00:05:06,756
We're gonna have a b-a-l-l here.
I guarantee you.

60
00:05:06,758 --> 00:05:11,427
A lot of people have termed this project
an experiment, and I can't disagree.

61
00:05:11,429 --> 00:05:13,729
What experiment would be complete...

62
00:05:13,731 --> 00:05:16,198
Without the scientists,

63
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:18,734
<i>I'd like to introduce</i>
two of the finest...

64
00:05:18,736 --> 00:05:21,637
<i>Psychological consultants</i>
that money can buy.

65
00:05:21,639 --> 00:05:25,574
And I wouldn't want you to get the impression
we're buying either of these gentlemen.

66
00:05:27,111 --> 00:05:29,512
Actually, the one on the end is rented,

67
00:05:29,514 --> 00:05:34,183
and the gentleman sitting
next to him is leased.

68
00:05:34,185 --> 00:05:35,918
<i>No, I'm kidding.</i>

69
00:05:35,920 --> 00:05:38,120
<i>The gentleman on the end...</i>
What can I say?

70
00:05:38,122 --> 00:05:42,291
He's from one of the most prestigious
institutes we have in this country.

71
00:05:42,293 --> 00:05:45,961
From Boulder, Colorado, from the
national institute of human behavior,

72
00:05:45,963 --> 00:05:50,166
would you welcome
Dr. Howard hill.

73
00:05:54,739 --> 00:05:57,139
And the gentleman sitting next to him...

74
00:05:57,141 --> 00:06:00,142
What can I say? You might have
seen him on some television shows.

75
00:06:00,144 --> 00:06:02,678
A well-known author.
He's written books.

76
00:06:02,680 --> 00:06:04,680
<i>From the university</i> of Minnesota,

77
00:06:04,682 --> 00:06:07,449
<i>please give a nice welcome</i>
to Dr. Ted cleary.

78
00:06:11,856 --> 00:06:14,390
A lot of you probably thought
Ted didn't stand up.

79
00:06:14,392 --> 00:06:17,593
Actually, he is standing. Isn't that great?
He eats very little.

80
00:06:19,797 --> 00:06:22,097
<i>You folks love to laugh,</i> don't you?

81
00:06:22,099 --> 00:06:26,001
Well, more than anything else in the world,
I'd love to get into some humor with you,

82
00:06:26,003 --> 00:06:28,170
but we really don't have the time.

83
00:06:28,172 --> 00:06:31,340
We're meeting the yeagers at the
airport in less than half an hour.

84
00:06:31,342 --> 00:06:34,877
So before yours truly
has to skidaddle out of here,

85
00:06:34,879 --> 00:06:38,247
I'd like, if I could,
to share my sentiments I have...

86
00:06:38,249 --> 00:06:42,451
About this beautiful city
with you, if I might.

87
00:06:42,453 --> 00:06:44,520
Mort!

88
00:06:46,257 --> 00:06:48,924
Ladies and gentleman, the man at
the piano, Mr. mort Lindsay...

89
00:06:48,926 --> 00:06:50,960
<i>From</i>
"the merv Griffin show."

90
00:06:50,962 --> 00:06:54,563
<i>And as much of his orchestra as</i>
we could afford to bring down.

91
00:06:58,769 --> 00:07:02,004
It's a little something I jotted down
on the plane coming in yesterday,

92
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:06,008
specially from me to you.

93
00:07:58,129 --> 00:08:01,463
Who are you? What do you do?
Paul lowell, lowell realty.

94
00:08:01,465 --> 00:08:04,166
Thanks very much for the house.
You got me my house.

95
00:08:04,168 --> 00:08:07,603
Who are you? Donna Stanley,
Stanley's gift shop at the airport.

96
00:08:07,605 --> 00:08:10,139
Thanks for that little
plastic cactus. Yes.

97
00:08:10,141 --> 00:08:12,074
And who are you?
I'm Jack from Cincinnati.

98
00:08:13,477 --> 00:08:15,477
You live down here?
Just visiting?

99
00:08:15,479 --> 00:08:17,479
No, I came down to watch you work.

100
00:08:17,481 --> 00:08:19,548
Isn't that something?
God bless you.

101
00:08:37,335 --> 00:08:39,134
Two grand!

102
00:08:49,246 --> 00:08:51,046
Thank you.

103
00:08:51,048 --> 00:08:54,116
God bless you!
You're something else!

104
00:08:55,519 --> 00:08:57,619
Thank you!

105
00:10:32,216 --> 00:10:34,149
Hello.

106
00:10:34,151 --> 00:10:38,620
So many of us go through life doing one
thing and dreaming of doing something else.

107
00:10:38,622 --> 00:10:41,356
I'm one of those people.
I'm in show business.

108
00:10:41,358 --> 00:10:44,293
I'm fortunate to have
that job, but quite frankly,

109
00:10:44,295 --> 00:10:47,296
if I'd studied harder
or been graded more fairly,

110
00:10:47,298 --> 00:10:51,200
I would have been a scientist
or a doctor of some kind.

111
00:10:51,202 --> 00:10:54,336
Well, the fulfillment of that
dream finally happened for me...

112
00:10:54,338 --> 00:10:58,340
When I arrived here at the national
institute of human behavior,

113
00:10:58,342 --> 00:11:00,242
a few miles southwest
of Boulder, Colorado.

114
00:11:01,645 --> 00:11:04,012
I knew from the inception
of this motion picture...

115
00:11:04,014 --> 00:11:08,517
That without scientific guidance from a
nationally recognized research organization,

116
00:11:08,519 --> 00:11:11,320
very few people
would take this seriously.

117
00:11:11,322 --> 00:11:13,522
However, with that guidance...

118
00:11:13,524 --> 00:11:16,225
We not only had a chance
at winning an Oscar,

119
00:11:16,227 --> 00:11:19,728
but possibly a nobel prize too.

120
00:11:19,730 --> 00:11:22,631
It gives me the chills.

121
00:11:22,633 --> 00:11:24,800
Let's go inside.

122
00:11:28,439 --> 00:11:31,173
Come on.

123
00:11:31,175 --> 00:11:35,010
Thousands of people responded
<i>to the advertisements...</i>

124
00:11:35,012 --> 00:11:37,346
<i>Scientifically placed</i> by the institute.

125
00:11:37,348 --> 00:11:41,617
<i>They filled out preliminary</i> questionnaires
in the privacy <i>of their own homes.</i>

126
00:11:41,619 --> 00:11:47,022
<i>Then, the 210 best families were</i>
invited here for final testing.

127
00:11:47,024 --> 00:11:51,093
<i>These tests in Boulder</i> were designed
to choose <i>the one family unit...</i>

128
00:11:51,095 --> 00:11:54,296
<i>That could best reflect</i> day-to-day
living <i>in contemporary America,</i>

129
00:11:55,099 --> 00:11:57,099
<i>and at the same time...</i>

130
00:11:57,101 --> 00:12:00,035
<i>Hold a motion picture audience</i>
completely spellbound.

131
00:12:00,037 --> 00:12:02,237
During the time they stayed here,

132
00:12:02,239 --> 00:12:06,842
the 210 families underwent
more than 145 separate tests,

133
00:12:06,844 --> 00:12:09,278
totaling more than 2,500 test hours.

134
00:12:09,280 --> 00:12:11,813
If these tests could be
converted into eggs,

135
00:12:11,815 --> 00:12:15,551
it would be enough to feed a city the size
of St. Louis for more than two years...

136
00:12:15,553 --> 00:12:18,487
On a two-egg-per-person
per week basis.

137
00:12:18,489 --> 00:12:21,924
Sound complicated?
It was, and very expensive.

138
00:12:21,926 --> 00:12:25,627
However, even though we were paying
for this, for top security reasons...

139
00:12:25,629 --> 00:12:28,197
The institute allowed us
to film just a small portion...

140
00:12:28,199 --> 00:12:30,933
Of a few of the tests.

141
00:12:32,136 --> 00:12:34,269
Honey, I completely believe that.

142
00:12:34,271 --> 00:12:38,173
Test 40, one of three
<i>role reversal exercises.</i>

143
00:12:38,175 --> 00:12:41,343
Be someone else in your family.

144
00:12:41,345 --> 00:12:45,514
<i>This test was invaluable,</i> not just because
of the insights <i>it gave into relationships,</i>

145
00:12:45,516 --> 00:12:50,552
<i>but because it single-handedly</i> discouraged
23 families <i>from further participation,</i>

146
00:12:50,554 --> 00:12:54,423
<i>saving us more than $90,000</i>
in wasted testing costs.

147
00:12:54,425 --> 00:12:57,926
I wanna go out and play. No! You
heard what your mother said.

148
00:12:57,928 --> 00:13:00,362
You have to stay in, do your
homework and be quiet all day.

149
00:13:01,932 --> 00:13:04,399
But I wanna go out and play. No!

150
00:13:04,401 --> 00:13:06,568
Well, I want to.
I said no!

151
00:13:06,570 --> 00:13:10,038
I said yes. I don't care what you say.
I'm the boss.

152
00:13:10,040 --> 00:13:12,207
Now you're gonna get a beating.

153
00:13:12,209 --> 00:13:14,977
I don't wanna do that.
Okay, okay. Harold, stop it!

154
00:13:14,979 --> 00:13:18,180
Don't call me Harold, call me "dad"!
Don't you hit me, you little...

155
00:13:18,182 --> 00:13:19,982
Damn you!

156
00:13:19,984 --> 00:13:22,551
All right.
<i>Thank you, folks.</i>

157
00:13:22,553 --> 00:13:24,553
<i>Thank you. Folks?</i>

158
00:13:24,555 --> 00:13:28,357
This was test 72, <i>one of 15 tests...</i>

159
00:13:28,359 --> 00:13:31,660
<i>Utilizing state-of-the-art</i>
computer technology.

160
00:13:31,662 --> 00:13:33,762
<i>This man...</i>

161
00:13:33,764 --> 00:13:37,666
<i>Was feeding all of</i>
his facial features into this...

162
00:13:37,668 --> 00:13:40,135
<i>The graphicon 8,000.</i>

163
00:13:40,137 --> 00:13:42,471
<i>This amazing computer</i>
would actually show...

164
00:13:42,473 --> 00:13:44,840
<i>What each family member's face</i>
would photograph like...

165
00:13:44,842 --> 00:13:46,908
<i>From every conceivable angle...</i>

166
00:13:46,910 --> 00:13:49,411
<i>And then give us</i> a digital readout
<i>of their screen presence.</i>

167
00:14:13,237 --> 00:14:15,270
Okay, it should be simple.

168
00:14:15,272 --> 00:14:20,709
Test 141, known simply
<i>as the driving test.</i>

169
00:14:20,711 --> 00:14:23,545
<i>Since much of anybody's life</i>
takes place in a car,

170
00:14:23,547 --> 00:14:27,516
<i>we wanted to make sure our</i>
family wasn't going to kill us.

171
00:14:27,518 --> 00:14:30,085
<i>Dummies, acting as cameramen,</i>
were placed...

172
00:14:30,087 --> 00:14:34,456
<i>In one of the 200 cars in the</i>
institute's mobile test fleet.

173
00:14:34,458 --> 00:14:36,825
When I tell you to start,
put the car in reverse,

174
00:14:36,827 --> 00:14:39,027
back it up to that simulated garage. Go?

175
00:14:39,029 --> 00:14:41,930
In reverse and back
in there. Okay, fine.

176
00:14:53,277 --> 00:14:55,517
You were supposed to put it back
in the simulated garage.

177
00:14:57,014 --> 00:14:59,815
What simulated garage?
Okay.

178
00:14:59,817 --> 00:15:01,917
While the testing continued,

179
00:15:01,919 --> 00:15:05,454
ground rules for the project
were slowly being developed.

180
00:15:05,456 --> 00:15:07,956
Most important was
the unusual agreement...

181
00:15:07,958 --> 00:15:11,593
That only the studio and a few of
the doctors at the institute...

182
00:15:11,595 --> 00:15:15,263
Would actually be allowed to see
the film as it was being shot.

183
00:15:15,265 --> 00:15:17,546
The rest of us would have
to wait until the year was over.

184
00:15:18,736 --> 00:15:21,536
This was done to reduce
possible confusion...

185
00:15:21,538 --> 00:15:24,039
And to heighten the reality.

186
00:15:24,041 --> 00:15:26,108
But, to really heighten the reality,

187
00:15:26,110 --> 00:15:29,578
we needed a whole new generation
of motion picture equipment...

188
00:15:29,580 --> 00:15:32,748
Equipment that could stay
out of our family's way.

189
00:15:32,750 --> 00:15:36,551
Two systems were chosen.
First, from Japan,

190
00:15:36,553 --> 00:15:40,255
special heat-sensing
wall cameras like this.

191
00:15:40,257 --> 00:15:42,524
These would be installed
wherever feasible.

192
00:15:42,526 --> 00:15:46,061
<i>These amazing devices</i>
actually used body heat...

193
00:15:46,063 --> 00:15:48,130
<i>To focus in</i> on the nearest person.

194
00:15:48,132 --> 00:15:52,434
Quiet, efficient, expensive.

195
00:15:52,436 --> 00:15:55,337
And then, to capture what those couldn't,

196
00:15:55,339 --> 00:15:57,873
a startling breakthrough in technology.

197
00:15:57,875 --> 00:16:00,542
The smallest, most versatile
motion picture camera ever made.

198
00:16:02,312 --> 00:16:07,549
From Holland,
the entanour 226-xl.

199
00:16:07,551 --> 00:16:11,653
The etanour is actually worn
over the head.

200
00:16:13,223 --> 00:16:15,891
The camera is controlled
by using body movement,

201
00:16:15,893 --> 00:16:20,529
and by operating this
human eye-like lens system.

202
00:16:22,966 --> 00:16:24,766
Isn't that something?

203
00:16:24,768 --> 00:16:27,235
And it can hear like a human too...

204
00:16:27,237 --> 00:16:29,771
With these special
Omni-directional microphones...

205
00:16:29,773 --> 00:16:31,573
Located exactly where we have our ears.

206
00:16:33,744 --> 00:16:35,577
The etanour needs no special lighting.

207
00:16:37,848 --> 00:16:41,249
And it uses no film.

208
00:16:41,251 --> 00:16:43,885
Yes, all picture and sound information...

209
00:16:43,887 --> 00:16:47,989
Is recorded digitally on
these integrated circuit chips,

210
00:16:47,991 --> 00:16:50,759
some no larger than a child's fingernail.

211
00:16:50,761 --> 00:16:53,061
When these chips are filled to capacity,

212
00:16:53,063 --> 00:16:57,199
they will be removed from this housing,
and then mailed back to the institute,

213
00:16:57,201 --> 00:17:01,336
where they're decoded and then
transferred to film as we know it.

214
00:17:01,338 --> 00:17:04,239
Only six of these cameras were ever made.

215
00:17:04,241 --> 00:17:06,842
Only five of them ever worked.

216
00:17:06,844 --> 00:17:09,644
We had four of those.

217
00:17:09,646 --> 00:17:11,646
<i>After six weeks of testing,</i>

218
00:17:11,648 --> 00:17:13,815
<i>the families had been</i>
narrowed down to two:

219
00:17:13,817 --> 00:17:19,254
<i>The Andrew feltons</i>
from green bay, Wisconsin,

220
00:17:19,256 --> 00:17:22,123
<i>and the Warren yeagers</i>
from Phoenix, Arizona.

221
00:17:22,125 --> 00:17:25,627
<i>Using the sophisticated</i> equipment and
the institute's <i>direct-mail facility,</i>

222
00:17:25,629 --> 00:17:28,630
<i>the other hundreds of families</i>
were notified...

223
00:17:28,632 --> 00:17:31,132
<i>That they were unsuitable.</i>

224
00:17:42,012 --> 00:17:45,113
<i>Since these two finalists</i>
had never met before,

225
00:17:45,115 --> 00:17:49,117
<i>each family served as</i> a matching
set of strangers <i>for the other.</i>

226
00:17:49,119 --> 00:17:52,320
<i>They were given</i> only one instruction
for <i>the hour-long encounter:</i>

227
00:17:52,322 --> 00:17:54,322
<i>Be yourselves.</i>

228
00:17:54,324 --> 00:17:57,158
You're with t.W.A.?
No, American.

229
00:18:02,099 --> 00:18:06,768
You get to fly for free, don't you?
We have to pay tax.

230
00:18:06,770 --> 00:18:09,204
